When my best friend Izzy, showed up at my apartment with a three year old and medical papers, I knew my life was about to change. She had always been the dramatic type, the kind who turned a paper cut into a medical emergency. But this time her voice cracked when she spoke. It's cancer. Aggressive. The doctors say six months at most. I stared at the papers showing test results. I couldn't understand. Her daughter January sat on my my couch eating goldfish crackers and watching cartoons. I need you to adopt her, Izzy said. It wasn't a question. Her dad's gone and my parents are dead. You're all she has. I wanted to say no. I was 28 and single, with a demanding job at a marketing firm. But Izzy had been my college roommate and the closest thing I had to a sister. So I said yes. The adoption happened fast. Izzy. His health deteriorated quicker than expected. She made me promise to never tell Jenny the truth about how sick she was. Let her think I loved her enough to make sure she'd be okay. She said from her hospice bed, she'd already set up a two million dollar life insurance policy with Jenny as the beneficiary, to be held in trust until she turned 21. For her future, Izzy whispered. Three weeks later, she was gone. Closed casket. The cancer had ravaged her. Body too much for viewing. Raising Jenny was harder than I imagined. She had nightmares constantly. She'd wake up screaming for her mommy, and I'd hold her until she fell back asleep. I gave up promotions to be home for school pickups. I stopped dating because January needed ability. When she was 11, she asked why her real mom left her. I told her Izzy loved her so much she made sure she'd always be taken care of. January didn't buy it. If she loved me, she would have stayed, she said. The teenage years were brutal. January attempted suicide when she was 15 after a particularly bad identity crisis. I spent my entire savings on therapy and treatment. I sold my car to pay for a specialized program. My boss threatened to fire me for missing so much work, but I didn't care. January needed me. Slowly, painfully, we worked through her trauma together. When she was 17, she called me mom for the first time. Not by accident, on purpose. Thanks, mom, she said. After I picked her up from school. I cried the whole drive home. By the time January turned 20, we built a real life together. She was pre med at Columbia with a full scholarship. She'd been secretly saving money from her part time job to buy me a car since she knew I'd sold mine for her treatment. You gave up everything for me, she said. I want to give something back. She Had plans for the insurance money, too. She wanted to start a foundation for kids who lost parents to cancer. Maybe something good can come from the bad, she said. That's when weird things started happening. Fresh flower disappeared on Izzy's grave that I didn't leave. January got an anonymous birthday card that said, almost time, sweetheart. I saw a woman at January's graduation who looked exactly like Izzy. She disappeared before I could get close. A private investigator started calling, asking about Izzy's death and the insurance policy. He said he was hired to locate beneficiaries. My gut told me something was wrong. The week before January's 21st birthday, I was making her favorite lasagna when the doorbell rang. I opened it and nearly fainted. Izzy stood there, very much alive, with a man in an expensive suit. Hi, bestie, she said, with that same dramatic flair. I'm here for what's mine. My brain couldn't process what I would. Seeing Izzy explained it all like she was telling me about her day. She paid off a hospice worker to fake the death certificate. She'd been living in Costa Rica under a fake name. She'd been watching us through January's Instagram for years, waiting for this moment. The man was her lawyer. He handed me papers claiming the adoption was done under false pretence.

We've known each other forever, but honestly, we've grown into totally different people. She's got this whole new friend group now and I don't really vibe with them. Still, I go because she's important to me. But there's one person who makes it miserable every single time, Amanda. Do you even eat? Does your boyfriend care that you don't have curves? Your legs are like sticks? The record, I eat plenty. I've just always had a fast metabolism. It's not something I control and it's not something I brag about. But her comments hit me right in my insecurities. I try to act unbothered, but it makes my skin crawl. And the worst part is she does it in front of people. It's embarrassing. This year I seriously considered not going. I even told my mom I might skip it. That's when she gave me an idea. She said, why don't you just treat it like she's giving you a compliment? If she says you're so skinny, you smile and say, thanks, I love being skinny. If she looks disappointed, then you'll know she was trying to insult you. It actually sounded Perfect, calm, simple and a little bit petty in a way that wouldn't get me in trouble. What I didn't tell my mom, though, was that Amanda is plus size. Honestly, I didn't think it mattered because I wouldn't be commenting on her body, just mine. Party day comes, two hour drive. I walk in, hug my friend, start making small talk and within minutes, no surprise, Amanda's at it. She glances at my arms and says, wow, so tiny. I brush it off. Then later we're in a little group, drinks in hand, and I can feel her eyes on me. She's scanning me from head to toe. Then she laughs, shakes her head and says loud enough for everyone to hear, god, you're so skinny. This was it. My moment. I turned to her, gave her my sweetest smile and said, thanks. I love being skinny. I swear to you. She slapped me. Not a playful tap, not a joke, a full on open handed slap across my face. Sound was loud enough that the music might as well have stopped. My head turned with the impact and I just froze there, hand on my cheek, staring at her in total shock. The whole room went silent. People were looking at us like they couldn't believe what just happened. Then out of nowhere, she starts sobbing, like full on ugly crying. She covers her face, bolts out of the room and two of her friends rush after her. Everyone else mostly just glaring at me like I was the one who'd crossed the line. Only my childhood friend and one other girl even bothered to ask if I was okay. I just mumbled something and grabbed my bag. I wasn't about to hang around after that. I drove two hours for this party, plan to stay overnight and left within hours. The next morning, I get a text from my childhood friend. She says she doesn't condone Amanda slapping me, but she thinks I was insensitive for saying I loved being skinny in front of a plus size woman. I told her Amanda has been making digs at me for years, never once commented on her body. I only talked about mine. She said it's different because being skinny is socially acceptable and that my comment triggered Amanda. I reminded her that Amanda has repeatedly triggered me with her constant jabs. I finally responded in a way that wasn't even insulting. She didn't really have a comeback for that, just that Amanda was going through a lot and wouldn't normally act like that. But I can't help thinking if the roles were reversed and I've been making comments about her body for years, people would be telling me I was out of line, not defending me. So, yeah, years of taking it, staying quiet, pretending it didn't bother me. One time I flipped the script and defend myself without a single insult aimed at her and she slapped Me for it and everyone acted like I was the problem.

He works two jobs related to his field, one as a chef in a restaurant and two as a cooking instructor. I had no real experience in cooking, but he encouraged me to learn and helped my skills improve. Even though he has a habit of rating every meal I cook. For example, X meal gets 7 out of 10 or y meal gets 8.3 out of 10, or even Z meal would have gotten 9 out of 10 if the sauce wasn't so salty, etc. I didn't feel great with him rating my food no matter the score, but he says he's helping me improve. So my family came over to visit and I wanted to cook their favorite meals. Gary sat with my parents and chatted till the food was ready. He started eating and kept making comments about my choice of meals. Once he put his fork down, he cleared his throat and literally started rating every dish I made. 7 out of 10 for this, 4.8 out of 10 for this, and 6 out of 10 for that. My family were so confused and I was floored. I felt awful as he kept giving advice.

voice_to_text: You know, in the deserts of the United States, there are witches who wear the skin of animals to become them. They're called skinwalkers. Once healers, now cursed. They sacrifice family to gain forbidden power. After that, they can shift into coyotes, owls, wolves. But something always stays human. The eyes, the hunger. A Navajo elder once said he saw a massive wolf walking upright. Its jaw too wide and its voice whispering in a human tongue. In 1997, two teens were driving near Ship Rock at night. They hit what looked like a dog. It screamed like a man. They got out, but the road was empty except for a trail of blood leading into the brush. Then came the knocking on the car roof, windows and finally, the windshield. A face stared in, mouth sewn shut, eyes burning red. It dropped to all fours and vanished into the dark. When they got home, claw marks covered the trunk. A scrap of fur was wedged in the door, still warm. Locals say, if you hear three knocks at night, don't open the door. If you dream of an animal watching you, don't sleep the next night. If you see footprints that turn from paws to bare feet, run. The skinwalkers are still out there, shifting, waiting. And if you ever hear breathing outside your window, just remember, they never come alone.

voice_to_text: Fathers, what's the worst thing you've ever done? I called the cops on my own seventeen year old son. It started small. Jordan came home with these brand new Jordans. The two hundred dollar ones. When I asked where he got them, he mumbled something about saving birthday money. But his birthday was eight months ago and I knew exactly how much he had. Then I found a roll of twenties in his backpack while looking for his report card. Three hundred bucks, rubber banded tight. When I confronted him, he said his friend owed him money from lawn work. But Jordan had never touched our lawn mower. He started coming home at weird hours, missing dinner. His grades dropped from b's to D's. Teachers called about absences I didn't know about. When I asked where he was, he'd just grunt and disappear into his room. The worst part was watching him change. My funny, smart kid turned cold. He'd snap at his little sister for asking to play video games. Started slamming doors. Stopped eating meals with us. His mom and I tried everything. Took his phone, grounded him. Nothing worked. voice_to_text: This is a true story. In the late 1960s, dozens of children across the US began reporting the same thing. A man in a clown suit standing outside schools, hiding near parks, or offering rides in a van with no windows. Police dismissed the stories at first. They said it was mass hysteria, the prank. But then kids started disappearing. The man was described as tall, wearing a faded clown costume, red gloves, and face paint that looked wrong, smudged, almost rotting. Parents reported seeing a massive white van parked near playgrounds, always moving. Just before police arrived. Some claimed they saw more than one clown inside, laughing, watching. Newspapers refused to print the story. No official reports were released. But in 1968, a boy from Ohio went missing after saying, the funny man asked me to see his balloon. They never found the child. Over the next year, similar sightings happened in Illinois, Pennsylvania and Georgia. Some say it was a group, a gang, that used the costumes as a cover. Others believe it was something darker hidden beneath the paint. To this day, no one was ever arrested. No names, no faces, just drawings and old case files, all showing the same thing. A clown with black eyes and a smile that never moved.
